# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: webp-format
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] An **image file format** is a file format for a digital image.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] There are many formats that can be used, such as JPEG, PNG, and GIF.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] Most formats up until 2022 were for storing 2D images, not 3D ones.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] The data stored in an image file format may be compressed or uncompressed.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] If the data is compressed, it may be done so using lossy compression or lossless compression.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] For graphic design applications, vector formats are often used.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] Some image file formats support transparency.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] A 3D image can be represented within a 2D format, as in a stereogram or autostereogram, but this 3D image will not be a true light field, and thereby may cause the vergence–accommodation conflict.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] Image files are composed of digital data in one of these formats so that the data can be displayed on a digital (computer) display or printed out using a printer.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] A common method for displaying digital image information has historically been rasterization.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] The size of raster image files is positively correlated with the number of pixels in the image and the color depth (bits per pixel).
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] Images can be compressed in various ways, however.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] A compression algorithm stores either an exact representation or an approximation of the original image in a smaller number of bytes that can be expanded back to its uncompressed form with a corresponding decompression algorithm.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] Images with the same number of pixels and color depth can have very different compressed file sizes.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] Considering exactly the same compression, number of pixels, and color depth for two images, different graphical complexity of the original images may also result in very different file sizes after compression due to the nature of compression algorithms.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] With some compression formats, images that are less complex may result in smaller compressed file sizes.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] This characteristic sometimes results in a smaller file size for some lossless formats than lossy formats.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] For example, graphically simple images (i.e., images with large continuous regions like line art or animation sequences) may be losslessly compressed into a GIF or PNG format and result in a smaller file size than a lossy JPEG format.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] With vector images, the file size increases only with the addition of more vectors.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] There are two types of image file compression algorithms: lossless and lossy.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] Lossless compression algorithms reduce file size while preserving a perfect copy of the original uncompressed image.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] Lossless compression generally, but not always, results in larger files than lossy compression.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] Lossless compression should be used to avoid accumulating stages of re-compression when editing images.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] Lossy compression algorithms preserve a representation of the original uncompressed image that may appear to be a perfect copy, but is not a perfect copy.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] Often lossy compression is able to achieve smaller file sizes than lossless compression.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] Most lossy compression algorithms allow for variable compression that trades image quality for file size.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] Including proprietary types, there are hundreds of image file types.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] The PNG, JPEG, and GIF formats are most often used to display images on the Internet.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] Some of these graphic formats are listed and briefly described below, separated into the two main families of graphics: raster and vector.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] Raster images are further divided into formats primarily aimed at (web) delivery (i.e., supporting relatively strong compression) versus formats primarily aimed at authoring or interchange (uncompressed or only relatively weak compression).
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] In addition to straight image formats, Metafile formats are portable formats that can include both raster and vector information.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] Examples are application-independent formats such as WMF and EMF.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] The metafile format is an intermediate format.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] Most applications open metafiles and then save them in their own native format.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] Page description language refers to formats used to describe the layout of a printed page containing text, objects, and images.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] JPEG (Joint Photographic Experts Group) is a lossy compression method; JPEG-compressed images are usually stored in the JFIF (JPEG File Interchange Format) or the Exif (Exchangeable Image File Format) file format.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] The JPEG filename extension is JPG or JPEG.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] Nearly every digital camera can save images in the JPEG format, which supports eight-bit grayscale images and 24-bit color images (eight bits each for red, green, and blue).
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] JPEG applies lossy compression to images, which can result in a significant reduction of the file size.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] Applications can determine the degree of compression to apply, and the amount of compression affects the visual quality of the result.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] When not too great, the compression does not noticeably affect or detract from the image's quality, but JPEG files suffer generational degradation when repeatedly edited and saved.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] The GIF (Graphics Interchange Format) is in normal use limited to an 8-bit palette, or 256 colors (while 24-bit color depth is technically possible).
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] GIF is most suitable for storing graphics with few colors, such as simple diagrams, shapes, logos, and cartoon-style images, as it uses LZW lossless compression, which is more effective when large areas have a single color and less effective for photographic or dithered images.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] Due to GIF's simplicity and age, it achieved almost universal software support.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] Due to its animation capabilities, it is still widely used to provide image animation effects, despite its low compression ratio compared to modern video formats.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] The PNG (Portable Network Graphics) file format was created as a free, open-source alternative to GIF.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] The PNG file format supports 8-bit (256 colors) paletted images (with optional transparency for all palette colors) and 24-bit truecolor (16 million colors) or 48-bit truecolor with and without an alpha channel – while GIF supports only 8-bit palettes with a single transparent color.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] Compared to JPEG, PNG excels when the image has large, uniformly colored areas.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] Even for photographs – where JPEG is often the choice for final distribution since its lossy compression typically yields smaller file sizes – PNG is still well-suited to storing images during the editing process because of its lossless compression.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] PNG provides a patent-free replacement for GIF (though GIF is itself now patent-free) and can also replace many common uses of TIFF.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] Indexed-color, grayscale, and truecolor images are supported, plus an optional alpha channel.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] The Adam7 interlacing allows an early preview, even when only a small percentage of the image data has been transmitted—useful in online viewing applications like web browsers.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] PNG can store gamma and chromaticity data, as well as ICC profiles, for accurate color matching on heterogeneous platforms.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] Animated formats derived from PNG are MNG and APNG, which is backwards compatible with PNG and supported by most browsers.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] JPEG 2000 is a compression standard enabling both lossless and lossy storage.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] The compression methods used are different from the ones in standard JFIF/JPEG; they improve quality and compression ratios, but also require more computational power to process.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] JPEG 2000 also adds features that are missing in JPEG.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] It is not nearly as common as JPEG but it is used currently in professional movie editing and distribution (some digital cinemas, for example, use JPEG 2000 for individual movie frames).
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] WebP is an open image format released in 2010 that uses both lossless and lossy compression.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] It was designed by Google to reduce image file size to speed up web page loading: its principal purpose is to supersede JPEG as the primary format for photographs on the web.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] WebP is based on VP8's intra-frame coding and uses a container based on RIFF.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] In 2011, Google added an "Extended File Format" allowing WebP support for animation, ICC profile, XMP and Exif metadata, and tiling.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] The support for animation allowed for converting older animated GIFs to animated WebP.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] The WebP container (i.e., RIFF container for WebP) allows feature support over and above the basic use case of WebP (i.e., a file containing a single image encoded as a VP8 key frame).
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] Most typical raster formats cannot store HDR data (32 bit floating point values per pixel component), which is why some relatively old or complex formats are still predominant here, and worth mentioning separately.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] Newer alternatives are showing up, though.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] RGBE is the format for HDR images originating from Radiance and also supported by Adobe Photoshop.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] JPEG-HDR is a file format from Dolby Labs similar to RGBE encoding, standardized as JPEG XT Part 2.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] JPEG XT Part 7 includes support for encoding floating point HDR images in the base 8-bit JPEG file using enhancement layers encoded with four profiles (A-D); Profile A is based on the RGBE format and Profile B on the XDepth format from Trellis Management.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] The High Efficiency Image File Format (HEIF) is an image container format that was standardized by MPEG on the basis of the ISO base media file format.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] While HEIF can be used with any image compression format, the HEIF standard specifies the storage of HEVC intra-coded images and HEVC-coded image sequences taking advantage of inter-picture prediction.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] AVIF is an image container, that is used to store AV1 encoded images.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] It was created by Alliance for open media (AOMedia) and is completely open source and royalty-free.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] It supports encoding images in 8, 10 and 12-bit depth.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] JPEG XL is a royalty-free raster-graphics file format that supports both lossy and lossless compression.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] It supports reversible recompression of existing JPEG files, as well as high-precision HDR (up to 32-bit floating point values per pixel component).
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] It is designed to be usable for both delivery and authoring use cases.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] The TIFF (Tag Image File Format) format is a flexible format usually using either the TIFF or TIF filename extension.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] The tag structure was designed to be easily extendible, and many vendors have introduced proprietary special-purpose tags – with the result that no one reader handles every flavor of TIFF file.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] TIFFs can be lossy or lossless, depending on the technique chosen for storing the pixel data.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] Some offer relatively good lossless compression for bi-level (black&white) images.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] Some digital cameras can save images in TIFF format, using the LZW compression algorithm for lossless storage.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] TIFF image format is not widely supported by web browsers, but it remains widely accepted as a photograph file standard in the printing business.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] TIFF can handle device-specific color spaces, such as the CMYK defined by a particular set of printing press inks.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] OCR (Optical Character Recognition) software packages commonly generate some form of TIFF image (often monochromatic) for scanned text pages.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] The BMP file format (Windows bitmap) is a raster-based, device-independent file type designed in the early days of computer graphics.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] It handles graphic files within the Microsoft Windows OS.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] Typically, BMP files are uncompressed and therefore large and lossless; their advantage is their simple structure and wide acceptance in Windows programs.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] Netpbm format is a family including the portable pixmap file format (PPM), the portable graymap file format (PGM), and the portable bitmap file format (PBM).
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] These are either pure ASCII files or raw binary files with an ASCII header that provide very basic functionality and serve as a lowest common denominator for converting pixmap, graymap, or bitmap files between different platforms.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] Several applications refer to them collectively as PNM (Portable Any Map).
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] As opposed to the raster image formats above (where the data describes the characteristics of each individual pixel), vector image formats contain a geometric description which can be rendered smoothly at any desired display size.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] At some point, all vector graphics must be rasterized in order to be displayed on digital monitors.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] Vector images may also be displayed with analog CRT technology such as that used in some electronic test equipment, medical monitors, radar displays, laser shows and early video games.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] Plotters are printers that use vector data rather than pixel data to draw graphics.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] CGM (Computer Graphics Metafile) is a file format for 2D vector graphics, raster graphics, and text, and is defined by ISO/IEC 8632.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] All graphical elements can be specified in a textual source file that can be compiled into a binary file or one of two text representations.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] CGM provides a means of graphics data interchange for computer representation of 2D graphical information independent from any particular application, system, platform, or device.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] It has been adopted to some extent in the areas of technical illustration and professional design, but has largely been superseded by formats such as SVG and DXF.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] The Gerber format (aka Extended Gerber, RS-274X) is a 2D bi-level image description format developed by Ucamco.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] It is the de facto standard format for printed circuit board or PCB software.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] SVG (Scalable Vector Graphics) is an open standard created and developed by the World Wide Web Consortium to address the need (and attempts of several corporations) for a versatile, scriptable and all-purpose vector format for the web and otherwise.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] The SVG format does not have a compression scheme of its own, but due to the textual nature of XML, an SVG graphic can be compressed using a program such as gzip.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] Because of its scripting potential, SVG is a key component in web applications: interactive web pages that look and act like applications.
[src:webp-format/image-file-format] These are formats containing both pixel and vector data, possible other data, e.g. the interactive features of PDF.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] By operation of the pigeonhole principle, no lossless compression algorithm can shrink the size of all possible data: Some data will get longer by at least one symbol or bit.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] Compression algorithms are usually effective for human- and machine-readable documents and cannot shrink the size of random data that contain no redundancy.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] Different algorithms exist that are designed either with a specific type of input data in mind or with specific assumptions about what kinds of redundancy the uncompressed data are likely to contain.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] Lossless data compression is used in many applications.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] For example, it is used in the ZIP file format and in the GNU tool gzip.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] It is also often used as a component within lossy data compression technologies (e.g. lossless mid/side joint stereo preprocessing by MP3 encoders and other lossy audio encoders).
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] Lossless compression is used in cases where it is important that the original and the decompressed data be identical, or where deviations from the original data would be unfavourable.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] Common examples are executable programs, text documents, and source code.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] Some image file formats, like PNG or GIF, use only lossless compression, while others like TIFF and MNG may use either lossless or lossy methods.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] Lossless audio formats are most often used for archiving or production purposes, while smaller lossy audio files are typically used on portable players and in other cases where storage space is limited or exact replication of the audio is unnecessary.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] The primary encoding algorithms used to produce bit sequences are Huffman coding (also used by the deflate algorithm) and arithmetic coding.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] Arithmetic coding achieves compression rates close to the best possible for a particular statistical model, which is given by the information entropy, whereas Huffman compression is simpler and faster but produces poor results for models that deal with symbol probabilities close to 1.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] There are two primary ways of constructing statistical models: in a *static* model, the data is analyzed and a model is constructed, then this model is stored with the compressed data.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] This approach is simple and modular, but has the disadvantage that the model itself can be expensive to store, and also that it forces using a single model for all data being compressed, and so performs poorly on files that contain heterogeneous data.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] *Adaptive* models dynamically update the model as the data is compressed.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] Both the encoder and decoder begin with a trivial model, yielding poor compression of initial data, but as they learn more about the data, performance improves.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] Most popular types of compression used in practice now use adaptive coders.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] Lossless compression methods may be categorized according to the type of data they are designed to compress.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] While, in principle, any general-purpose lossless compression algorithm (*general-purpose* meaning that they can accept any bitstring) can be used on any type of data, many are unable to achieve significant compression on data that are not of the form for which they were designed to compress.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] Many of the lossless compression techniques used for text also work reasonably well for indexed-color images.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] These techniques take advantage of the specific characteristics of images such as the common phenomenon of contiguous 2-D areas of similar tones.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] Every pixel but the first is replaced by the difference to its left neighbor.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] This leads to small values having a much higher probability than large values.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] This is often also applied to sound files, and can compress files that contain mostly low frequencies and low volumes.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] For images, this step can be repeated by taking the difference to the top pixel, and then in videos, the difference to the pixel in the next frame can be taken.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] The adaptive encoding uses the probabilities from the previous sample in sound encoding, from the left and upper pixel in image encoding, and additionally from the previous frame in video encoding.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] In the wavelet transformation, the probabilities are also passed through the hierarchy.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] Many of these methods are implemented in open-source and proprietary tools, particularly LZW and its variants.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] Some algorithms are patented in the United States and other countries and their legal usage requires licensing by the patent holder.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] However, the patents on LZW expired on June 20, 2003.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] As mentioned previously, lossless sound compression is a somewhat specialized area.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] Lossless sound compression algorithms can take advantage of the repeating patterns shown by the wave-like nature of the data‍—‍essentially using autoregressive models to predict the "next" value and encoding the (possibly small) difference between the expected value and the actual data.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] If the difference between the predicted and the actual data (called the *error*) tends to be small, then certain difference values (like 0, +1, −1 etc. on sample values) become very frequent, which can be exploited by encoding them in few output bits.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] It is sometimes beneficial to compress only the differences between two versions of a file (or, in video compression, of successive images within a sequence).
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] This is called delta encoding (from the Greek letter Δ, which in mathematics, denotes a difference), but the term is typically only used if both versions are meaningful outside compression and decompression.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] For example, while the process of compressing the error in the above-mentioned lossless audio compression scheme could be described as delta encoding from the approximated sound wave to the original sound wave, the approximated version of the sound wave is not meaningful in any other context.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] No lossless compression algorithm can efficiently compress all possible data .
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] For this reason, many different algorithms exist that are designed either with a specific type of input data in mind or with specific assumptions about what kinds of redundancy the uncompressed data are likely to contain.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] Some of the most common lossless compression algorithms are listed below.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] Cryptosystems often compress data (the "plaintext") *before* encryption for added security.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] When properly implemented, compression greatly increases the unicity distance by removing patterns that might facilitate cryptanalysis.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] However, many ordinary lossless compression algorithms produce headers, wrappers, tables, or other predictable output that might instead make cryptanalysis easier.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] Thus, cryptosystems must utilize compression algorithms whose output does not contain these predictable patterns.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] Genetics compression algorithms (not to be confused with genetic algorithms) are the latest generation of lossless algorithms that compress data (typically sequences of nucleotides) using both conventional compression algorithms and specific algorithms adapted to genetic data.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] In 2012, a team of scientists from Johns Hopkins University published the first genetic compression algorithm that does not rely on external genetic databases for compression.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] HAPZIPPER was tailored for HapMap data and achieves over 20-fold compression (95% reduction in file size), providing 2- to 4-fold better compression much faster than leading general-purpose compression utilities.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] Genomic sequence compression algorithms, also known as DNA sequence compressors, explore the fact that DNA sequences have characteristic properties, such as inverted repeats.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] The most successful compressors are XM and GeCo.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] For eukaryotes XM is slightly better in compression ratio, though for sequences larger than 100 MB its computational requirements are impractical.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] Self-extracting executables contain a compressed application and a decompressor.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] When executed, the decompressor transparently decompresses and runs the original application.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] This is especially often used in demo coding, where competitions are held for demos with strict size limits, as small as 1 kilobyte.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] This type of compression is not strictly limited to binary executables, but can also be applied to scripts, such as JavaScript.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] Lossless compression algorithms and their implementations are routinely tested in head-to-head benchmarks.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] There are a number of better-known compression benchmarks.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] Some benchmarks cover only the data compression ratio, so winners in these benchmarks may be unsuitable for everyday use due to the slow speed of the top performers.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] Another drawback of some benchmarks is that their data files are known, so some program writers may optimize their programs for best performance on a particular data set.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] The winners on these benchmarks often come from the class of context-mixing compression software.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] The Compression Ratings website published a chart summary of the "frontier" in compression ratio and time.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] The **Silesia corpus** is a collection of files that was created in 2003 as an alternative for the Canterbury corpus and Calgary corpus, based on concerns about how well these represented modern files.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] It contains various data types, including large text documents, executable files, and databases.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] It is widely used in data compression research.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] The corpus consists of 12 files, totaling 211MB.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] The files were chosen to represent what the author considered to be data types likely to grow rapidly in size over time, such as computer programs and databases, along with more traditional compression benchmarks, such as large text files.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] Because it has a broader and more modern selection of datatypes, it is considered a better source of test data for compression algorithms when compared to the Calgary corpus.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] Lossless data compression algorithms cannot guarantee compression for all input data sets.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] In other words, for any lossless data compression algorithm, there will be an input data set that does not get smaller when processed by the algorithm, and for any lossless data compression algorithm that makes at least one file smaller, there will be at least one file that it makes larger.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] Most practical compression algorithms provide an "escape" facility that can turn off the normal coding for files that would become longer by being encoded.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] In theory, only a single additional bit is required to tell the decoder that the normal coding has been turned off for the entire input; however, most encoding algorithms use at least one full byte (and typically more than one) for this purpose.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] For example, deflate compressed files never need to grow by more than 5 bytes per 65,535 bytes of input.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] In fact, if we consider files of length N, if all files were equally probable, then for any lossless compression that reduces the size of some file, the expected length of a compressed file (averaged over all possible files of length N) must necessarily be *greater* than N.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] So if we know nothing about the properties of the data we are compressing, we might as well not compress it at all.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] A lossless compression algorithm is useful only when we are more likely to compress certain types of files than others; then the algorithm could be designed to compress those types of data better.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] Thus, the main lesson from the argument is not that one risks big losses, but merely that one cannot always win.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] To choose an algorithm always means implicitly to select a *subset* of all files that will become usefully shorter.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] This is the theoretical reason why we need to have different compression algorithms for different kinds of files: there cannot be any algorithm that is good for all kinds of data.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] Algorithms are generally quite specifically tuned to a particular type of file: for example, lossless audio compression programs do not work well on text files, and vice versa.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] In particular, files of random data cannot be consistently compressed by any conceivable lossless data compression algorithm; indeed, this result is used to *define* the concept of randomness in Kolmogorov complexity.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] It is provably impossible to create an algorithm that can losslessly compress any data.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] Such an algorithm contradicts fundamental laws of mathematics because, if it existed, it could be applied repeatedly to losslessly reduce any file to length 1.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] On the other hand, it has also been proven that there is no algorithm to determine whether a file is incompressible in the sense of Kolmogorov complexity.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] Hence it is possible that any particular file, even if it appears random, may be significantly compressed, even including the size of the decompressor.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] An example is the digits of the mathematical constant *pi*, which appear random but can be generated by a very small program.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] However, even though it cannot be determined whether a particular file is incompressible, a simple theorem about incompressible strings shows that over 99% of files of any given length cannot be compressed by more than one byte (including the size of the decompressor).
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] Abstractly, a compression algorithm can be viewed as a function on sequences (normally of octets).
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] Compression is successful if the resulting sequence is shorter than the original sequence (and the instructions for the decompression map).
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] For a compression algorithm to be lossless, the compression map must form an injection from "plain" to "compressed" bit sequences.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] The pigeonhole principle prohibits a bijection between the collection of sequences of length *N* and any subset of the collection of sequences of length *N*−1.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] Therefore, it is not possible to produce a lossless algorithm that reduces the size of every possible input sequence.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] Real compression algorithm designers accept that streams of high information entropy cannot be compressed, and accordingly, include facilities for detecting and handling this condition.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] An obvious way of detection is applying a raw compression algorithm and testing if its output is smaller than its input.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] Sometimes, detection is made by heuristics; for example, a compression application may consider files whose names end in ".zip", ".arj" or ".lha" uncompressible without any more sophisticated detection.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] A common way of handling this situation is quoting input, or uncompressible parts of the input in the output, minimizing the compression overhead.
[src:webp-format/lossless-compression] For example, the zip data format specifies the 'compression method' of 'Stored' for input files that have been copied into the archive verbatim.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] In information technology, **lossy compression**, or **irreversible compression**, is the class of data compression methods that uses inexact approximations and partial data discarding to represent the content.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] These techniques are used to reduce data size for storing, handling, and transmitting content.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] Higher degrees of approximation create coarser images as more details are removed.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] This is opposed to lossless data compression (reversible data compression) which does not degrade the data.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] The amount of data reduction possible using lossy compression is much higher than using lossless techniques.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] Well-designed lossy compression technology often reduces file sizes significantly before degradation is noticed by the end-user.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] Even when noticeable by the user, further data reduction may be desirable (e.g., for real-time communication or to reduce transmission times or storage needs).
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] The most widely used lossy compression algorithm is the discrete cosine transform (DCT), first published by Nasir Ahmed, T.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] Lossy compression is most commonly used to compress multimedia data (audio, video, and images), especially in applications such as streaming media and internet telephony.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] By contrast, lossless compression is typically required for text and data files, such as bank records and text articles.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] It can be advantageous to make a master lossless file which can then be used to produce additional copies from.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] This allows one to avoid basing new compressed copies on a lossy source file, which would yield additional artifacts and further unnecessary information loss.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] It is possible to compress many types of digital data in a way that reduces the size of a computer file needed to store it, or the bandwidth needed to transmit it, with no loss of the full information contained in the original file.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] A picture, for example, is converted to a digital file by considering it to be an array of dots and specifying the color and brightness of each dot.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] The original data contains a certain amount of information, and there is a lower bound to the size of a file that can still carry all the information.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] Basic information theory says that there is an absolute limit in reducing the size of this data.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] When data is compressed, its entropy increases, and it cannot increase indefinitely.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] For example, a compressed ZIP file is smaller than its original, but repeatedly compressing the same file will not reduce the size to nothing.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] Most compression algorithms can recognize when further compression would be pointless and would in fact increase the size of the data.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] In many cases, files or data streams contain more information than is needed.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] For example, a picture may have more detail than the eye can distinguish when reproduced at the largest size intended; likewise, an audio file does not need a lot of fine detail during a very loud passage.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] Developing lossy compression techniques as closely matched to human perception as possible is a complex task.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] Sometimes the ideal is a file that provides exactly the same perception as the original, with as much digital information as possible removed; other times, perceptible loss of quality is considered a valid tradeoff.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] The terms "irreversible" and "reversible" are preferred over "lossy" and "lossless" respectively for some applications, such as medical image compression, to circumvent the negative implications of "loss".
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] The type and amount of loss can affect the utility of the images.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] Artifacts or undesirable effects of compression may be clearly discernible yet the result still useful for the intended purpose.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] Or lossy compressed images may be 'visually lossless', or in the case of medical images, so-called diagnostically acceptable irreversible compression (DAIC) may have been applied.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] Some forms of lossy compression can be thought of as an application of transform coding, which is a type of data compression used for digital images, digital audio signals, and digital video.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] The transformation is typically used to enable better (more targeted) quantization.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] Knowledge of the application is used to choose information to discard, thereby lowering its bandwidth.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] The remaining information can then be compressed via a variety of methods.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] When the output is decoded, the result may not be identical to the original input, but is expected to be close enough for the purpose of the application.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] The most common form of lossy compression is a transform coding method, the discrete cosine transform (DCT), which was first published by Nasir Ahmed, T.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] DCT is the most widely used form of lossy compression, for popular image compression formats (such as JPEG), video coding standards (such as MPEG and H.264/AVC) and audio compression formats (such as MP3 and AAC).
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] In the case of audio data, a popular form of transform coding is perceptual coding, which transforms the raw data to a domain that more accurately reflects the information content.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] For example, rather than expressing a sound file as the amplitude levels over time, one may express it as the frequency spectrum over time, which corresponds more accurately to human audio perception.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] This is because uncompressed audio can only reduce file size by lowering bit rate or depth, whereas compressing audio can reduce size while maintaining bit rate and depth.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] This compression becomes a selective loss of the least significant data, rather than losing data across the board.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] Further, a transform coding may provide a better domain for manipulating or otherwise editing the data – for example, equalization of audio is most naturally expressed in the frequency domain (boost the bass, for instance) rather than in the raw time domain.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] From this point of view, perceptual encoding is not essentially about *discarding* data, but rather about a *better representation* of data.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] Another use is for backward compatibility and graceful degradation: in color television, encoding color via a luminance-chrominance transform domain (such as YUV) means that black-and-white sets display the luminance, while ignoring the color information.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] Lossy compression formats suffer from generation loss: repeatedly compressing and decompressing the file will cause it to progressively lose quality.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] This is in contrast with lossless data compression, where data will not be lost via the use of such a procedure.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] Information-theoretical foundations for lossy data compression are provided by rate-distortion theory.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] Much like the use of probability in optimal coding theory, rate-distortion theory heavily draws on Bayesian estimation and decision theory in order to model perceptual distortion and even aesthetic judgment.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] In some systems the two techniques are combined, with transform codecs being used to compress the error signals generated by the predictive stage.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] The advantage of lossy methods over lossless methods is that in some cases a lossy method can produce a much smaller compressed file than any lossless method, while still meeting the requirements of the application.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] Lossy methods are most often used for compressing sound, images or videos.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] This is because these types of data are intended for human interpretation where the mind can easily "fill in the blanks" or see past very minor errors or inconsistencies – ideally lossy compression is transparent (imperceptible), which can be verified via an ABX test.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] Data files using lossy compression are smaller in size and thus cost less to store and to transmit over the Internet, a crucial consideration for streaming video services such as Netflix and streaming audio services such as Spotify.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] When a user acquires a lossily compressed file, (for example, to reduce download time) the retrieved file can be quite different from the original at the bit level while being indistinguishable to the human ear or eye for most practical purposes.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] Many compression methods focus on the idiosyncrasies of human physiology, taking into account, for instance, that the human eye can see only certain wavelengths of light.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] The psychoacoustic model describes how sound can be highly compressed without degrading perceived quality.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] Flaws caused by lossy compression that are noticeable to the human eye or ear are known as compression artifacts.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] The compression ratio (that is, the size of the compressed file compared to that of the uncompressed file) of lossy video codecs is nearly always far superior to that of the audio and still-image equivalents.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] An important caveat about lossy compression (formally transcoding), is that editing lossily compressed files causes digital generation loss from the re-encoding.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] This can be avoided by only producing lossy files from (lossless) originals and only editing (copies of) original files, such as images in raw image format instead of JPEG.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] If data which has been compressed lossily is decoded and compressed losslessly, the size of the result can be comparable with the size of the data before lossy compression, but the data already lost cannot be recovered.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] When deciding to use lossy conversion without keeping the original, format conversion may be needed in the future to achieve compatibility with software or devices (format shifting), or to avoid paying patent royalties for decoding or distribution of compressed files.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] By modifying the compressed data directly without decoding and re-encoding, some editing of lossily compressed files without degradation of quality is possible.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] Editing which reduces the file size as if it had been compressed to a greater degree, but without more loss than this, is sometimes also possible.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] The primary programs for lossless editing of JPEGs are `jpegtran`, and the derived `exiftran` (which also preserves Exif information), and Jpegcrop (which provides a Windows interface).
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] These allow the image to be cropped, rotated, flipped, and flopped, or even converted to grayscale (by dropping the chrominance channel).
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] While unwanted information is destroyed, the quality of the remaining portion is unchanged.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] Some other transforms are possible to some extent, such as joining images with the same encoding (composing side by side, as on a grid) or pasting images such as logos onto existing images (both via Jpegjoin), or scaling.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] The freeware Windows-only IrfanView has some lossless JPEG operations in its `JPG_TRANSFORM` plugin.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] Metadata, such as ID3 tags, Vorbis comments, or Exif information, can usually be modified or removed without modifying the underlying data.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] Some well-known designs that have this capability include JPEG 2000 for still images and H.264/MPEG-4 AVC based Scalable Video Coding for video.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] Such schemes have also been standardized for older designs as well, such as JPEG images with progressive encoding, and MPEG-2 and MPEG-4 Part 2 video, although those prior schemes had limited success in terms of adoption into real-world common usage.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] Similar techniques are used in mipmaps, pyramid representations, and more sophisticated scale space methods.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] Some audio formats feature a combination of a lossy format and a lossless correction which when combined reproduce the original signal; the correction can be stripped, leaving a smaller, lossily compressed, file.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] Such formats include MPEG-4 SLS (Scalable to Lossless), WavPack, OptimFROG DualStream, and DTS-HD Master Audio in lossless (XLL) mode).
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] Researchers have performed lossy compression on text by either using a thesaurus to substitute short words for long ones, or generative text techniques, although these sometimes fall into the related category of lossy data conversion.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] A general kind of lossy compression is to lower the resolution of an image, as in image scaling, particularly decimation.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] One may also remove less "lower information" parts of an image, such as by seam carving.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] Many media transforms, such as Gaussian blur, are, like lossy compression, irreversible: the original signal cannot be reconstructed from the transformed signal.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] However, in general these will have the same size as the original, and are not a form of compression.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] Lowering resolution has practical uses, as the NASA New Horizons craft transmitted thumbnails of its encounter with Pluto-Charon before it sent the higher resolution images.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] Another solution for slow connections is the usage of Image interlacing which progressively defines the image.
[src:webp-format/lossy-compression] Thus a partial transmission is enough to preview the final image, in a lower resolution version, without creating a scaled and a full version too.
[src:webp-format/vp8] Initially released as a proprietary successor to On2's previous VP7 format, VP8 was released as an open and royalty-free format in May 2010 after Google acquired On2 Technologies.
[src:webp-format/vp8] Google provided an irrevocable patent promise on its patents for implementing the VP8 format, and released a specification of the format under the Creative Commons Attribution 3.0 license.
[src:webp-format/vp8] That same year, Google also released libvpx, the reference implementation of VP8, under the revised BSD license.
[src:webp-format/vp8] Opera, Firefox, Chrome, Pale Moon, and Chromium support playing VP8 video in HTML video tag.
[src:webp-format/vp8] Internet Explorer officially supports VP8 if the user has the DirectShow filter installed.
[src:webp-format/vp8] According to Google, VP8 is mainly used in connection with WebRTC and as a format for short looped animations, as a replacement for the Graphics Interchange Format (GIF).
[src:webp-format/vp8] VP8 can be multiplexed into the Matroska-based container format WebM along with Vorbis and Opus audio.
[src:webp-format/vp8] The image format WebP is based on VP8's intra-frame coding.
[src:webp-format/vp8] VP8's direct successor, VP9, and the royalty-free AV1 codec from the Alliance for Open Media are based on VP8.
[src:webp-format/vp8] VP8 only supports progressive scan video signals with 4:2:0 chroma subsampling and 8 bits per sample.
[src:webp-format/vp8] In its first public version, On2's VP8 implementation supports multi-core processors with up to 64 cores simultaneously.
[src:webp-format/vp8] At least in the implementation (from August 2011), VP8 is comparatively badly adapted to high resolutions (HD).
[src:webp-format/vp8] With only three reference frame buffers needed, VP8 enables decoder implementations with a relatively small memory footprint.
[src:webp-format/vp8] The format features a pure intra mode, i.e. using only independently coded frames without temporal prediction, to enable random access in applications like video editing.
[src:webp-format/vp8] VP8 is a traditional block-based transform coding format.
[src:webp-format/vp8] It has much in common with H.264, e.g. some prediction modes.
[src:webp-format/vp8] At the time of first presentation of VP8, according to On2 the in-loop filter and the Golden Frames were among the novelties of this iteration.
[src:webp-format/vp8] The first definition of such a filter is already found in the H.263 standard, though, and Golden Frames were already in use in VP5 and VP7.
[src:webp-format/vp8] The discrete cosine transform (DCT) on 4×4 blocks and the Walsh–Hadamard transform (WHT) serve as basic frequency transforms.
[src:webp-format/vp8] A maximum of three frames can be referenced for temporal prediction: the last Golden Frame (may be an intra frame), alternate reference frame, and the directly preceding frame.
[src:webp-format/vp8] The so-called alternate reference frames (altref) can serve as reference-only frames for displaying them can be deactivated.
[src:webp-format/vp8] In this case, the encoder can fill them with arbitrary useful image data, even from future frames, and thereby serve the same purpose as the b-frames of the MPEG formats.
[src:webp-format/vp8] Similar macroblocks can be assigned to one of up to four (even spatially disjoint) segments and thereby share parameters like the reference frame used, quantizer step size, or filter settings.
[src:webp-format/vp8] VP8 offers two different adjustable deblocking filters that are integrated into the codec loops (in-loop filtering).
[src:webp-format/vp8] Many coding tools use probabilities that are calculated continuously from recent context, starting at each intra frames.
[src:webp-format/vp8] Macro blocks can comprise 4×4, 8×8, or 16×16 samples.
[src:webp-format/vp8] Motion vectors have quarter-pixel precision.
[src:webp-format/vp8] VP8 was first released by On2 Technologies on September 13, 2008, as On2 TrueMotion VP8, replacing its predecessor, VP7.
[src:webp-format/vp8] After Google acquired On2 in February 2010, calls for Google to release the VP8 source code were made.
[src:webp-format/vp8] Most notably, the Free Software Foundation issued an open letter on March 12, 2010, asking Google to gradually replace the usage of Adobe Flash Player and H.264 on YouTube with a mixture of HTML5 and a freed VP8.
[src:webp-format/vp8] Word of an impending open-source release announcement got out on April 12, 2010.
[src:webp-format/vp8] On May 19, at its Google I/O conference, Google released the VP8 codec software under a BSD-like license and the VP8 bitstream format specification under an irrevocable free patent license.
[src:webp-format/vp8] This made VP8 the second product from On2 Technologies to be opened, following their donation of the VP3 codec in 2002 to the Xiph.Org Foundation, from which they derived the Theora codec.
[src:webp-format/vp8] In February 2011, MPEG LA invited patent holders to identify patents that may be essential to VP8 in order to form a joint VP8 patent pool.
[src:webp-format/vp8] As a result, in March the United States Department of Justice (DoJ) started an investigation into MPEG LA for its role in possibly attempting to stifle competition.
[src:webp-format/vp8] In July 2011, MPEG LA announced that 12 patent holders had responded to its call to form a VP8 patent pool, without revealing the patents in question, and despite On2 having gone to great lengths to avoid such patents.
[src:webp-format/vp8] In November 2011, the Internet Engineering Task Force published the informational RFC 6386, VP8 Data Format and Decoding Guide.
[src:webp-format/vp8] This deal has cleared the way for possible MPEG standardisation as its royalty-free internet video codec, after Google submitted VP8 to the MPEG committee in January 2013.
[src:webp-format/vp8] In March 2013, Nokia asserted a patent claim against HTC and Google for the use of VP8 in Android in a German court; however, on August 5, 2013, the webm project announced that the German court has ruled that VP8 does not infringe Nokia's patent.
[src:webp-format/vp8] Nokia has made an official intellectual property rights (IPR) declaration to the IETF with respect to the VP8 Data Format and Decoding Guide listing 64 granted patents and 22 pending patent applications.
[src:webp-format/vp8] The reference implementation of a VP8 (and VP9) codec is found in the programming library libvpx which is released as free software.
[src:webp-format/vp8] It has a mode for one-pass and two-pass encoding, respectively, while the one-pass mode is known as being broken and not offering effective control over the target bitrate.
[src:webp-format/vp8] Currently, libvpx is primary software library capable of encoding VP8 video streams, but at least one independent implementation exists in ffvp8enc.
[src:webp-format/vp8] A Video for Windows wrapper of the VP8 codec based on the Google VP8 library (FourCC: VP80) is available.
[src:webp-format/vp8] The WebM Project hardware team in Finland released an RTL hardware encoder for VP8 that is available at no cost for semiconductor manufacturers.
[src:webp-format/vp8] The Nvidia Tegra mobile chipsets have full VP8 hardware encoding and decoding (since Tegra 4).
[src:webp-format/vp8] libvpx is capable of decoding VP8 video streams.
[src:webp-format/vp8] On July 23, 2010, Fiona Glaser, Ronald Bultje, and David Conrad of the FFmpeg Team announced the ffvp8 decoder.
[src:webp-format/vp8] Through testing, they determined that ffvp8 was faster than Google's own libvpx decoder.
[src:webp-format/vp8] The WebM Project hardware team released an RTL hardware decoder for VP8, that is releasable to semiconductor companies at zero cost.
[src:webp-format/vp8] TATVIK Technologies announced a VP8 decoder that is optimized for the ARM Cortex-A8 processor.
[src:webp-format/vp8] Marvell's ARMADA 1500-mini chipset has VP8 SD and HD hardware decoding support (used in Chromecast).
[src:webp-format/vp8] Intel has full VP8 decoding support built into their Bay Trail chipsets.
[src:webp-format/vp8] Intel Broadwell also adds VP8 hardware decoding support.
[src:webp-format/vp8] Also on May 19, 2010, the WebM Project was launched, featuring contributions from "Mozilla, Opera, Google and more than forty other publishers, software and hardware vendors" in a major effort to use VP8 as the video format for HTML5.
[src:webp-format/vp8] In the WebM container format, the VP8 video is used with Vorbis or Opus audio.
[src:webp-format/vp8] Internet Explorer 9 will support VP8 video playback if the proper codec is installed.
[src:webp-format/vp8] Android is WebM-enabled from version 2.3 - Gingerbread.
[src:webp-format/vp8] Since Android 4.0, VP8 could be read inside mkv and WebM could be streamed.
[src:webp-format/vp8] Adobe also announced that the Flash Player will support VP8 playback in a future release.
[src:webp-format/vp8] On September 30, 2010, Google announced WebP, their new image format, on the Chromium blog.
[src:webp-format/vp8] WebP is based on VP8's intra-frame coding and uses a container based on Resource Interchange File Format (RIFF).
[src:webp-format/vp8] While H.264/MPEG-4 AVC contains patented technology and requires licenses from patent holders and limited royalties for hardware, Google has irrevocably released the VP8 patents it owns under a royalty-free public license.
[src:webp-format/vp8] On the other hand, a review conducted by streamingmedia.com in May 2010 concluded that H.264 offers slightly better quality than VP8.
[src:webp-format/vp8] In September 2010 Fiona Glaser, a developer of the x264 encoder, gave several points of criticism for VP8, claiming that its specification was incomplete, and the performance of the encoder's deblocking filter was inferior to x264 in some areas.
[src:webp-format/vp8] In its specification, VP8 should be a bit better than H.264 Baseline Profile and Microsoft's VC-1.
[src:webp-format/vp8] Encoding is somewhere between Xvid and VC-1.
[src:webp-format/vp8] Decoding is slower than FFmpeg's H.264, but this aspect can hardly be improved due to the similarities to H.264.
[src:webp-format/vp8] Compression-wise, VP8 offers better performance than Theora and Dirac.
[src:webp-format/vp8] According to Glaser, the VP8 interface lacks features and is buggy, and the specification is not fully defined and could be considered incomplete.
[src:webp-format/vp8] Much of the VP8 code is copy-pasted C code, and since the source constitutes the actual specification, any bugs will also be defined as something that has to be implemented to be in compliance.
[src:webp-format/vp8] In 2010, it was announced that the WebM audio/video format would be based on a profile of the Matroska container format together with VP8 video and Vorbis audio.
[src:webp-format/webp] Google announced the WebP format in September 2010; the company released the first stable version of its supporting library in April 2018.
[src:webp-format/webp] WebP has seen widespread adoption across the Internet in order to reduce image size, with all major browsers currently supporting the format.
[src:webp-format/webp] WebP was first announced by Google on 30 September 2010 as a new open format for lossy compressed true-color graphics on the web, producing files that were smaller than JPEG files for comparable image quality.
[src:webp-format/webp] It was based on technology which Google had acquired with the purchase of On2 Technologies.
[src:webp-format/webp] As a derivative of the VP8 video format, it is a sister project to the WebM multimedia container format.
[src:webp-format/webp] WebP-related software is released under a BSD free software license.
[src:webp-format/webp] On 3 October 2011, Google added an "Extended File Format" allowing WebP support for animation, ICC profile, XMP and Exif metadata, and tiling (compositing very large images from maximum 16384 × 16384 tiles).
[src:webp-format/webp] Tiling support was never finalized and was removed from the spec again.
[src:webp-format/webp] On 18 November 2011, Google announced a new lossless compression mode, and support for transparency (alpha channel) in both lossless and lossy modes; support was enabled by default in libwebp 0.2.0 (16 August 2012).
[src:webp-format/webp] According to Google's measurements in November 2011, a conversion from PNG to WebP resulted in a 45% reduction in file size when starting with PNGs found on the web, and a 28% reduction compared to PNGs that are recompressed with pngcrush and PNGOUT.
[src:webp-format/webp] In July 2016, Apple added WebP support to early beta versions of macOS Sierra and iOS 10, but support was later removed in the GM seed versions of iOS 10 and macOS Sierra released in September 2016.
[src:webp-format/webp] In September 2020, WebP support was added in Safari version 14.
[src:webp-format/webp] The supporting libwebp library reached version 1.0 in April 2018.
[src:webp-format/webp] In November 2024, WebP was formally specified in and published as RFC 9649.
[src:webp-format/webp] WebP's lossy compression algorithm is based on the intra-frame coding of the VP8 video format and the Resource Interchange File Format (RIFF) as a container format.
[src:webp-format/webp] As such, it is a block-based transformation scheme with eight bits of color depth and a luminance–chrominance model with chroma subsampling by a ratio of 1:2 (YCbCr 4:2:0).
[src:webp-format/webp] Without further content, the mandatory RIFF container has an overhead of only twenty bytes, though it can also hold additional metadata.
[src:webp-format/webp] The side length of WebP images is limited to 16383 pixels.
[src:webp-format/webp] Each block is predicted on the values from the three blocks above it and from one block to the left of it (block decoding is done in raster-scan order: left to right and top to bottom).
[src:webp-format/webp] There are four basic modes of block prediction: horizontal, vertical, DC (one color), and TrueMotion.
[src:webp-format/webp] Mispredicted data and non-predicted blocks are compressed in a 4×4 pixel sub-block with a discrete cosine transform or a Walsh–Hadamard transform.
[src:webp-format/webp] Both transforms are done with fixed-point arithmetic to avoid rounding errors.
[src:webp-format/webp] The output is compressed with entropy encoding.
[src:webp-format/webp] WebP also has explicit support for parallel decoding.
[src:webp-format/webp] The reference implementation consists of converter software in the form of a command-line program for Linux (cwebp) and a programming library for the decoding, the same as for WebM.
[src:webp-format/webp] The open-source community ported the converter to other platforms, such as Windows.
[src:webp-format/webp] An image may have metadata stored in Exif or XMP formats.
[src:webp-format/webp] An image may have transparency, i.e., an alpha channel.
[src:webp-format/webp] An image may have an embedded ICC profile as described by the International Color Consortium.
[src:webp-format/webp] WebP's lossless compression, a newer algorithm unrelated to VP8, was designed by Google software engineer Jyrki Alakuijala.
[src:webp-format/webp] It uses advanced techniques such as dedicated entropy codes for different color channels, exploiting 2D locality of backward reference distances and a color cache of recently used colors.
[src:webp-format/webp] This complements basic techniques such as dictionary coding, Huffman coding and color indexing transform.
[src:webp-format/webp] This format uses a recursive definition: all of the control images, such as the local entropy code selection, are encoded the same way as the whole image itself.
[src:webp-format/webp] Google has proposed using WebP for animated images as an alternative to the popular GIF format, citing the advantages of 24-bit color with transparency, combining frames with lossy and lossless compression in the same animation, and support for seeking to specific frames.
[src:webp-format/webp] Google reports a 64% reduction in file size for images converted from animated GIFs to lossy WebP, and a 19% reduction for lossless WebP.
[src:webp-format/webp] As of 2024, web browsers that support WebP had 97% market share.
[src:webp-format/webp] The proprietary PageSpeed Insights tool suggests that webmasters switch from JPEG and PNG to WebP in order to improve their website speed score.
[src:webp-format/webp] Google Chrome and all Chromium-based browsers support WebP.
[src:webp-format/webp] Lossy WebP support was added to Chrome for desktop in version 17 (released February 2012) and lossless WebP support was added in version 23 (released November 2012); lossy and lossless support was added in Google Chrome for Android in version 25 (released March 2013).
[src:webp-format/webp] Microsoft Edge versions released after January 2020 are based on the Chromium browser, and have native WebP support.
[src:webp-format/webp] EdgeHTML-based versions of Microsoft Edge support WebP through a platform extension (installed by default) (unless running in the security-hardened "Application Guard" mode, which does not support platform extensions).
[src:webp-format/webp] Safari added support for WebP in September 2020 with iOS 14 and macOS Big Sur.
[src:webp-format/webp] Mozilla Firefox officially supports WebP since January 2019.
[src:webp-format/webp] It was initially considered for implementation in 2013.
[src:webp-format/webp] Pale Moon implemented initial support for WebP in January 2016 with its version 26 milestone.
[src:webp-format/webp] SeaMonkey began supporting WebP with its version 2.53.5 released in November 2020.
[src:webp-format/webp] GNOME Web, Midori, and Falkon natively support WebP.
[src:webp-format/webp] WebP can also be displayed in all major browsers using the WebPJS JavaScript library, although support in Internet Explorer 6 and above is achieved using Flash.
[src:webp-format/webp] Support for WebP was added to Links in version 2.26.
[src:webp-format/webp] After WebP was announced in September 2010, software gradually began to support it.
[src:webp-format/webp] By 2011, there were plugins for several popular graphics software programs to support WebP, and some programs such as Acorn and Pixelmator had added native support.
[src:webp-format/webp] Over time, support for the WebP format has grown.
[src:webp-format/webp] In 2019, Google released a free plug-in that enables WebP support in earlier versions of Adobe Photoshop.
[src:webp-format/webp] Free Photoshop plug-ins had been released by Telegraphics and fnordware before that.
[src:webp-format/webp] GIMP up to version 2.8 also supported WebP via a plugin; later, this plugin was shipped in GIMP 2.9 branch, and received multiple improvements.
[src:webp-format/webp] Google has also released a plug-in for Microsoft Windows that enables WebP support in Windows Photo Viewer, Microsoft Office 2010, FastPictureViewer, and any other application that uses Windows Imaging Component.
[src:webp-format/webp] FFmpeg linked with the VP8/VP9 reference codec library *libvpx* can extract VP8 key frames from WebM media and a script can then add the WebP RIFF header and the NUL pad byte for odd frame lengths.
[src:webp-format/webp] Meanwhile, FFmpeg supports *libwebp* directly.
[src:webp-format/webp] Gmail and Google Photos both support WebP.
[src:webp-format/webp] Support for WebP is also planned for Google App Engine.
[src:webp-format/webp] The *Instant Previews* feature of Google Search uses WebP internally to reduce disk space used by previews.
[src:webp-format/webp] Android 4.0 supports encoding and decoding WebP images (via bitmap and Skia).
[src:webp-format/webp] SDL_image supports the format since 1.2.11.
[src:webp-format/webp] Sumatra PDF supports WebP images for both standalone files and comic books since version 2.4.
[src:webp-format/webp] Telegram Messenger uses WebP for its Stickers, claiming they are displayed five times faster compared to the other formats usually used in messaging apps.
[src:webp-format/webp] Signal uses WebP for its non-animated stickers.
[src:webp-format/webp] LibreOffice supports the import of WebP images since version 7.4, so does the LibreOffice technology based online office Collabora Online.
[src:webp-format/webp] Godot Engine as of version 4.0 supports importing and exporting WebP images and uses WebP as its internal format for storing imported compressed textures.
[src:webp-format/webp] Content management systems (CMS) usually do not support WebP natively or by default.
[src:webp-format/webp] However, for most popular CMS, extensions are available for automated conversion from other image formats to WebP and delivering WebP images to compatible browsers.
[src:webp-format/webp] Since June 2021, WordPress supports WebP natively.
[src:webp-format/webp] Social media services known to natively support WebP in messages include Facebook, Slack, Discord and Element; however, some of these services only support static WebP, and not animated WebP.
[src:webp-format/webp] Like VP8 on which it is based, lossy WebP supports only 8-bit YUV 4:2:0 format, which may cause color loss on images with thin contrast elements (such as in pixel art and computer graphics) and ghosting in anaglyph.
[src:webp-format/webp] Lossless WebP supports VP8L encoding that works exclusively with 8-bit RGBA (red, green, blue, alpha) color space.
[src:webp-format/webp] It has no support for 10-bit color depth, while the successors HEIC and AVIF added 10-bit color depth support.
[src:webp-format/webp] Due to the complexity of their compression method, WebP files take significantly more time to create than other web image formats.
[src:webp-format/webp] It is therefore not always advisable to process WebP images on demand, for example in the context of Web Map Services.
[src:webp-format/webp] In October 2013, Josh Aas from Mozilla Research published a comprehensive study of current lossy encoding techniques and was not able to conclude that WebP outperformed JPEG by any significant margin.
[src:webp-format/webp] The extensive use of libwebp packages across hundreds of applications, from web browsers to mobile apps, posed a major patching challenge to mitigate the vulnerability, due to the demanding pre-release testing requirements, which highlights the wide-scale implications of this vulnerability.
[src:webp-format/webp] Several web browsers—including Google Chrome, Firefox, Microsoft Edge, and Brave—issued security patches following the discovery of the vulnerability.
[src:webp-format/webp] The vulnerability was ultimately patched in libwebp version 1.3.2.
[src:webp-format/webp] Google began developing a second version of WebP, plainly named WebP 2, in June 2021, the goal of which was to reach similar compression ratios as AVIF's while remaining faster to encode and decode; its reference implementation is `libwebp2`.
[src:webp-format/webp] On 12 October 2022, Google changed the README file in WebP 2's development repository to state "WebP 2 will not be released as an image format" and described the version as a "playground for image compression experiments".
